What Cinch2D is:\
Cinch2D is essentially a very fancy billboarder: it creates rectangular polygons and textures them, then manages their position and depth, giving you a very simple interface, similar to Flash's ActionScript3 Sprite class.  The main components of Cinch2D are:\
1: The Stage class.  This is the main container for all Cinch2D stuff.  You add it to the main camera (more instructions below).\
2: The Sprite class.  Everything you see and interact with in Cinch2D will be a Sprite class instance.  It contains methods for creating objects from images and sprite sheets, handling mouse interaction, and positioning/scaling.\
3: The Library class.  Creates Sprites.\
4: The Tween class.  Just like good ol' AS3 tweens.  Lets you make much more engaging UI.\
5: The PhysicsContainer class.  Encapsulates a Farseer (Box2D) world.  Tutorial 9 has more details.\
\
Installation:\
You should see a Plugins/Cinch2D folder, if not, try importing it again.\
\
Things you absolutely must know:\
1: Never call Unity's standard Destroy method (e.g. Destroy(someCinchObjectInstance);).  This will usually crash the app.  Instead, call SomeCinchObjectInstance.Destroy().\
2: Don't use the normal Unity process of creating scripts (making a new gameObject and using AddComponent<>())  Instead, use the static methods on Sprite and Library to make new Cinch2D objects.  See tutorial 5 for more details.\
3: We had to hijack Start, Awake, Update, and LateUpdate for internal plumbing, so do this instead when dealing with Cinch2D objects:\
* Start(), Awake(): use OnAwake() instead\
* Update(): use OnEnterFrame(float time) instead\
* LateUpdate(): use OnExitFrame() instead\
